## Food APP Name

Circadian

# Reason for creating App

I created this app to simplify the meal creation process for chefs, allowing them to easily add or remove menu items with just a few taps. This flexibility not only saves time but also enables chefs to respond quickly to changing trends and customer preferences. One of the standout features is the app's capability to add dishes to a cart. This very helpful as it will allow the chef to track the best-selling dishes, providing valuable insights that help chefs understand their customers' tastes and optimize their menus accordingly. Furthermore, the app is made to be as user-friendly as possible, so even people with no prior tech knowledge may use it with ease. Chefs can easily manage their menus without feeling overwhelmed thanks to intuitive interfaces, guided lessons, and instant access to key elements.

# Code Summaries

The Home screen is the first screen to be navigated through easily thanks to the app's code structure. Every screen is made to highlight various features and content related to the goal of the application. \`Stack.Screen\` is used to define the navigation structure, which consists of the **Home**, **Menu**, **Category, Cart**, and **AddDish** screens.  
<br/>The app's first interface is represented by the **HomeScreen** component, which has a button that takes users to the Menu screen, a title, and a logo. Its simplistic user interface is designed to improve visual appeal. Subsequently, the **MenuScreen** component displays a neatly arranged menu comprising several food categories, accompanied by pictures, titles, and typical costs. This page gives users a clear overview of all the things that are accessible and lets them navigate by tapping on certain categories.  
<br/>Next, the **CategoryScreen** component allows users to interactively examine, add, and remove dishes while providing a detailed view of all the dishes inside a given category. Rendering dish items is more efficient when FlatList is used. The shopping cart experience is significantly enhanced with the **CartScreen** component, which enables customers to review the dish they have chosen, modify the amount, and view the entire cost. It also includes order confirmation capabilities. Finally, the **AddDishScreen** component displays a simple form where users may enter information about a new dish, including its name, price, and description. It is necessary for the dish management function of the app since, upon submission, it calls a function that adds the item to the menu. Furthermore these elements combine to produce a flawless user experience.

# AddDishScreen Summary

I can add new dishes to a list, with validation for the name, price, and description. While also being able to view existing dishes in a list format. The Chef can also Remove a dish from the list where then the updated list of dishes is passed back to the previous screen (CategoryScreen) using the setCourses function.
